\begin_layout Standard
Our goal is to find an analog of Gleason's theorem in the 
\family roman
\size normal
discrete quantum theory (DQT)
\family default
\size default
.
 The Born rule and Gleason's theorem in in conventional quantum theory (CQT)
 are reviewed in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Conventional-Quantum-Theory"

\end_inset

.
 The Born rule
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Mermin2007,inun.423549119950101"

\end_inset

 gives a probability on states for any mixed state, and conversely Gleason's
 theorem implies any probability corresponds to a state.
 In another word, instead of starting from states and the Born rule, the
 conventional quantum theory may be built from observables, and replace
 the Born rule by another set of definitions and axioms.
 Because the Born rule and Gleason's theorem are closely related, their
 DQT versions will be discussed in pair in each 
\family roman
attempt 
\family default
in the later sections after providing the necessary definitions for DQT
 in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Discrete-Quantum-Theory"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Because the original Born rule cannot be applied on finite fields directly,
 in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:First-Attempt"

\end_inset

, we introduce a coarse Born rule with the range 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{L}_{2}=\left\{ \text{impossible},\text{possible}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Although the coarse Born rule can be applied on finite fields giving a
 discrete Born rule., but 
\family roman
we cannot find corresponding Gleason's theorem because some probabilities
 don't correspond to any states.
 These probabilities exist because 
\family default

\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{L}_{2}$
\end_inset

 is a commutative monoid with the annihilation law 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
x\lor\textrm{possible}=\textrm{possible for all }x\in\mathscr{L}_{2}\textrm{ ,}\label{eq:annihilation}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which eliminates information.
 Hence, we know almost nothing about a variable if it is logical-or with
 other variables and the final result is possible.
 This exactly happens in the not
\family roman
 Gleason's theorem
\family default
s.
 In contrast, in conventional probability if we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
x+\frac{1}{2}=1\textrm{ ,}\label{eq:unique-solution}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

we can uniquely solve the equation with 
\begin_inset Formula $x=\frac{1}{2}$
\end_inset

.
 In general, these kind of equations can be uniquely solved in a group because
 every group element has its inverse element.
 
\end_layout

