\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "inun.425605319950101"

\end_inset

.
 The outcome 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 is a set.
 To simplify discussion, we will only consider finite 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

.
 For example, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega=\left\{ H,T\right\} $
\end_inset

 for coin-tossing.
 The event space 
\begin_inset Formula $\varSigma$
\end_inset

 are subsets of the outcome which we can test.
 When the outcome is finite, usually every subset of the outcome is considered
 as an event, i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $\varSigma=2^{\Omega}$
\end_inset

.
 For example, we can test 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

whether a coin is head or not after we toss it
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ H\right\} $
\end_inset

 is an event of coin-tossing.
 Finally, a classical probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 is a function from 
\begin_inset Formula $\varSigma$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Two events 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 are called exclusive if 
\begin_inset Formula $A\cap B=\textrm{Ã˜}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The simplest classical probability is coin-tossing.
 When we toss a coin, the only two outcomes are a head 
