The Born Rule
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\family roman
\size normal
When we measure an non-degenerated observable 
\begin_inset Formula ${\mathbf{O}}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula ${\mathbf{O}}\left|i\right\rangle =\lambda_{i}\left|i\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 on a system in a state 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\Psi}$
\end_inset

, the probability is given by the Born rule of CQT 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
{\cal P}_{\Psi}\left(\lambda_{i}\right)=\frac{\ip{\Psi}{i}\ip{i}{\Psi}}{\ip{\Psi}{\Psi}\ip{i}{i}}\textrm{ .}\label{prob1.eq-6}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula ${\cal P}_{\Psi}\left(\lambda_{i}\right)$
\end_inset

 only depends on the 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\Psi}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{i}$
\end_inset

, but not on any other eigenvectors or eigenvalues.
 Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal P}_{\Psi}$
\end_inset

 is actually a function on the set of state vectors 
\family default
\size default

\begin_inset Formula $\C^{d*}=\left\{ \ket{\Psi}\in\C^{d}\mid\ip{\Psi}{\Psi}\ne0\right\} $
\end_inset


\family roman
\size normal
, and can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
{\cal P}_{\Psi}\left(\ket{i}\right)=\frac{\ip{\Psi}{i}\ip{i}{\Psi}}{\ip{\Psi}{\Psi}\ip{i}{i}}\textrm{ .}\label{prob1.eq-6-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

If the system is in a mixed state represented by a density matrix 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\rho=\sum_{j}p_{j}\frac{\proj{\Psi_{j}}}{\ip{\Psi_{j}}{\Psi_{j}}}\textrm{ ,}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

the Born rule (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "prob1.eq-6"

\end_inset

) can be extended to 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
{\cal P}_{\rho}\left(\ket{i}\right) & = & \sum_{j}p_{j}{\cal P}_{\Psi_{j}}\left(\ket{i}\right)\textrm{ .}\label{prob.mixed}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are two important properties of 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal P}_{\rho}:\C^{d*}\rightarrow\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

.
 First, 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal P}_{\rho}$
\end_inset

 is invariant under scalar multiplication because a vector still represents
 the same state if we normalize it or multiply it by a global phase.
 Second, 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal P}_{\rho}$
\end_inset

 is a probability, and the total probability should be one.
 
\end_layout

