After we define the state vectors and the Hermitian dot product, we are
 ready to define Hermitian operators representing observables.
 As discussed in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Critical-Analysis-CQT"

\end_inset

, the measurement result of an observable
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{O}$
\end_inset

 is a real eigenvalue of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{O}$
\end_inset

.
 However, a Hermitian operator
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $\ff{p^{2}}$
\end_inset

 may not be qualified for an observable because 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}$
\end_inset

 may not have suitable eigenvalues and eigenvectors to define the measurement
 process, or equivalently 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}$
\end_inset

 is not unitarily diagonalizable, for the following reasons: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\family roman
\size normal
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "enu:eigenvalueCount"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}$
\end_inset

 may lack eigenvalues.
 More precisely, the total multiplicity of eigenvalues of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\ff{p^{2}}$
\end_inset

 may be less than 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 is the multiplicity of an eigenvalue 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 means that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x-\lambda\right)^{K_{\lambda}}$
\end_inset

 is a factor of the characteristic polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\det\left(\mathbf{H}-x\mathds{1}\right)\textrm{ ,}\label{eq:characteristic}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

while 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x-\lambda\right)^{K_{\lambda}+1}$
\end_inset

 is not a factor of the characteristic polynomial.
 In another word, 
\begin_inset Formula $\ff{p^{2}}$
\end_inset

 is not algebraically closed
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DummitFoote2004"

\end_inset

.
 For example, consider a Hermitian matrix 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{H}_{1}=\left(\begin{array}{ccc}
-1 & -\rmi & 0\\
\rmi & 1 & -\rmi\\
0 & \rmi & 1
\end{array}\right)
\]

\end_inset

whose characteristic polynomials over 
\begin_inset Formula $\ff{9}$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\det\left(\mathbf{H}_{1}-x\mathds{1}\right) & = & 2x^{3}+x^{2}+2
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

which have no solution in 
\begin_inset Formula $\ff{9}$
\end_inset

 so that the total multiplicities is 0 less than 3.
 Hence, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}_{1}$
\end_inset

 should not be an observable because there is no eigenvalue as any measurement
 result.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\family roman
\size normal
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "enu:degeneracy"

\end_inset

The dimension of an eigenspace may be less than the multiplicity of its
 eigenvalue.
 For example, consider a Hermitian matrix 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{H}_{2}=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
-1 & -1-\rmi\\
-1+\rmi & 0
\end{array}\right)
\]

\end_inset

Over 
\begin_inset Formula $\ff{9}$
\end_inset

, its only eigenvalue is 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 of multiplicity 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

.
 The only eigenspace of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}_{2}$
\end_inset

 is spanned by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\begin{array}{cc}
1 & -1+\rmi\end{array}\right)^{T}$
\end_inset

.
 The dimension of the eigenspace is 1 less than 2 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}_{2}$
\end_inset

 are not diagonalizable over 
\begin_inset Formula $\ff{9}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}_{2}$
\end_inset

 were an observable, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}_{2}$
\end_inset

 would always have the measurement result 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 with the post-measurement state 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\begin{array}{cc}
1 & -1+\rmi\end{array}\right)^{T}$
\end_inset

.
 In another word, if we measured 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}_{2}$
\end_inset

 by the Stern-Gerlach experiment, we would always produce a 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\begin{array}{cc}
1 & -1+\rmi\end{array}\right)^{T}$
\end_inset

 beam without even splitting the input beam.
 This violates our intuitively of quantum measurement.
 Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}_{2}$
\end_inset

 should not be an observable.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

In order to understand the reason why 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}_{2}$
\end_inset

 is not diagonalizable, we can diagonalize 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}_{2}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\C$
\end_inset

.
 The eigenvalues of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}_{2}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\C$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $-2$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
-2 & \equiv & 1\left(\bmod3\right)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

In another word, two eigenvalues in 
\begin_inset Formula $\C$
\end_inset

 map to only one eigenvalue of multiplicity 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\ff{9}$
\end_inset

, and the corresponding two eigenspaces with dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\C$
\end_inset

 map to the same eigenspace still with dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\ff{9}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\family roman
\size normal
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "enu:orthonormal"

\end_inset

Some eigenvectors are zero-norm so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{H}$
\end_inset

